              "text": "For the Digo of Kenya's south coast, the question of what to wear has become, in the twenty-first century, a question of who to be. The forces that have shaped dress choices across the developing world — urbanization, formal employment, global media, religious movements, the sheer availability of cheap mass-produced Western clothing — have all reached the coast, and they have not arrived gently. The shift from traditional to modern dress is real, measurable, and generational. Older Digo men and women are more likely to wear traditional garments daily — the hando, the kikoy, the kanga, the kanzu. Younger Digo wear these primarily for ceremonies and cultural events, dressing in Western clothes or the buibui-and-hijab ensemble for their everyday lives. This shift is not unique to the Digo. It is the common story of indigenous dress cultures everywhere. But among the Digo, it has produced a distinctive counter-movement: a deliberate, creative effort to carry traditional textile elements forward into contemporary life."
