              "text": "The twentieth century brought changes that accelerated the transformation of Digo settlement patterns. Colonial land policies, the growth of Mombasa as an urban centre, the expansion of the tourism industry along the Diani coast, and the development of modern transport networks all reshaped where and how the Digo live. Some Digo families moved to urban areas for employment. Others found their traditional land absorbed into tourism developments or commercial agriculture. The dispersed village pattern persists in rural Kwale County, but it exists alongside newer patterns — peri-urban settlements, planned housing, and the informal settlements that fringe growing towns."
