              "text": "Behind the Swahili architectural style lies the long history of Arab engagement with the East African coast. Omani, Yemeni, and Persian traders and settlers brought building traditions from the Arabian Peninsula and the Gulf — the use of carved plasterwork, the enclosed courtyard house, the wind-catching tower, the emphasis on interior ornamentation rather than exterior display. These elements fused with African building practices and local materials to create the distinctive Swahili architectural vocabulary that, in turn, influenced communities like the Digo."
