              "text": "The traditional Digo house is a masterwork of environmental adaptation. Every material comes from the immediate landscape — the mangrove swamps that line the creeks and inlets, the coconut palms that define the coastal lowlands, the earth itself. No nails, no imported timber, no factory-made components. A Digo homestead is, in the most literal sense, built from the ground it stands on and the trees that surround it. This is not poverty of means but richness of knowledge — an intimate understanding of which materials perform best in the hot, humid conditions of the Kenya coast, refined over centuries of practice."
