              "text": "These thick mud walls are not merely structural. They are the house's climate control system. During the day, when coastal temperatures can reach the mid-thirties, the dense mud absorbs heat slowly, keeping the interior cool. At night, when temperatures drop and the coastal breeze picks up, the stored heat radiates inward, warming the house through the cooler hours. This thermal mass effect — the same principle used in adobe construction worldwide — makes the mud-walled house remarkably comfortable without any mechanical cooling or heating."
