              "text": "For generations, to be Digo was to be of the coast — rooted in the coconut groves and cashew plantations of Kwale, anchored to the rhythm of the monsoon seasons, defined by the proximity of the Indian Ocean. That equation has not been abandoned, but it has been complicated. Today, increasing numbers of Digo — especially the young — are leaving the rural villages of Kwale County for the cities, driven by the same forces that propel rural-to-urban migration across the developing world: the promise of employment, the pursuit of education, and the hope of a life that the village economy, with its limited diversification and chronic underinvestment, cannot provide."
